\f1\fs29\fsmilli14667 \cf2 One of the pleasurable impulses that drives literary-historical research is the feeling that one\'92s explorations are special. Often it can seem as if you are the first person to read, or to care about, a text or a person in hundreds of years. That intimacy across time gains its sacred aura in part from its exclusivity; to love Jane Austen has a very different tenor than if one loves Charlotte Smith, or loves Susannah Goodall. Sharing one\'92s discoveries is a double-edged sword: love asks to be shared, but if it is shared too successfully, one\'92s own love may be threatened with diminishment, lost in a more general and therefore less special love.
\f2\fs24 \

\f1\fs29\fsmilli14667 Selecting items completely at random may seem to be a poor methodology to find a new love. But what reparative reading shows us is that the object of love need not be worthy of that love; it may shape or colour the form of love, but the \'93plenitude\'94 comes from the lover, not the beloved. Any object becomes lovable when examined with a loving eye. To observe, in minute detail, is to love.
